ce:section.ce:para:
Previous studies have reported the photothermal efficacy of several photothermal agents in different preclinical studies. However, because of the non-specific binding of nanoparticles and the inclusion of NIR dye, there are inevitable side-effects [6,38,39]. To assure the competence and safety of photothermal ablation, focalized imaging is critically required, which can also help in the live tracking of photothermal agents and clear cut delineation of tumor boundaries from neighboring healthy tissue. Thus, in our study, the advancement of photothermal agents using HA and GQDs was carried out towards dye-free focalized imaging directed photothermal cancer therapy. Fabrication of the nanohybrids can be carried out using either the top-down or bottom-up approach. A top-down approach starts from a bulk material that is broken down into smaller units. It is generally the method of choice when NPs that are desired are in microscale range. In contrast, the bottom-up approach assembles materials from the nanoscale, to form a larger entity [40]. The increase in functionality achieved by layering and coating of the nanohybrid structure by various functional moieties can be easily manageable. Herein, we have utilized the bottom-up approach which utilizes the chemical and physical interaction between the functional moieties and nanohybrid structure for their successful integration. We have demonstrated a slow reduction process to achieve the controlled growth of gold shell over a soft polymeric core that is further functionalized with biocompatible HA targeting ligand and emissive GQDs as imaging probes (
                     Fig. 1
                     ).
